04227nam a22005775i 9780520939462DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20062006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209394627 a10.1525/97805209394622doi  a(DE-B1597)519379  a(OCoLC)70701709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML3917.C9bM66 2006eb 7aMUS0290002bisacsh04a780/.97291/09042221 aMoore, Robin D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMusic and Revolution :bCultural Change in Socialist Cuba /cRobin D. Moore. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (367 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMusic of the African Diaspora ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Music and the Arts in Socialist Cuba -- t1. Revelry and Revolution: The Paradox of the 1950s -- t2. Music and Social Change in the First Years -- t3. Artistic Institutions, Initiatives, and Policies -- t4. Dance Music and the Politics of Fun -- t5. Transformations in Nueva Trova -- t6. Afro-Cuban Folklore in a Raceless Society -- t7. Ay, Dios Ampárame: Sacred Music and Revolution -- t8. Music and Ideological Crisis -- tConclusion: Musical Politics into the New Millennium -- tAppendix: Publications on Music from Revolutionary Cuba -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMusic and Revolution provides a dynamic introduction to the most prominent artists and musical styles that have emerged in Cuba since 1959 and to the policies that have shaped artistic life. Robin D. Moore gives readers a chronological overview of the first decades after the Cuban Revolution, documenting the many ways performance has changed and emphasizing the close links between political and cultural activity. Offering a wealth of fascinating details about music and the milieu that engendered it, the author traces the development of dance styles, nueva trova, folkloric drumming, religious traditions, and other forms. He describes how the fall of the Soviet Union has affected Cuba in material, ideological, and musical terms and considers the effect of tense international relations on culture. Most importantly, Music and Revolution chronicles how the arts have become a point of negotiation between individuals, with their unique backgrounds and interests, and official organizations. It uses music to explore how Cubans have responded to the priorities of the revolution and have created spaces for their individual concerns.Copub: Center for Black Music Research  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMusicxHistory and criticismx20th centuryxCuba. 0aMusicxPolitical aspectsxCuba. 0aMusicxPolitical aspectszCuba. 0aMusiczCubay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSocialism and music. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Pop Vocal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520939462.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles